Gerko Vink

Load packages

set.seed(123)
library(mice)
library(dplyr)
library(magrittr)
library(readr)

Read in the data

The following data are obtained from Kaggle

data <- read_csv("Data/diabetes.csv", 
                 col_types = cols(Pregnancies = col_integer(), 
                                  Glucose = col_integer(), 
                                  BloodPressure = col_integer(), 
                                  SkinThickness = col_integer(), 
                                  Insulin = col_integer(), 
                                  Age = col_integer(), 
                                  Outcome = col_factor(levels = c("1", "0"))))
data %<>% mutate_at(vars(2:8), na_if, y = 0)
imp <- mice(data, m=1, maxit = 35, method = "pmm", print = FALSE)
plot(imp)

data <- complete(imp)

Aim

The aim is to mimic the investigations in this study on the Pima Indians Diabetes data set. To do so, we follow these steps:

  1. Formulate an analysis model
  2. Run the analysis model on the data set to obtain the true data inference
  3. Obtain statistical properties of the true data set, such as
  • mean()
  • variance()
  • cor()
  • etc.
  1. Plot the distributions of the true data set
  2. Simulate nsim = 1000 times the following:
    1. Ampute the data with ampute() for a MCAR mechanism
    1. Impute the data \(m\) times with mice for each of the following imputation methods:
    • mean imputation [mice.impute.mean]
    • regression imputation (best value prediction): [mice.impute.norm.predict]
    • stochastic regression imputation with \(m=1\) [mice.impute.norm.nob]
    • stochastic regression imputation with \(m=5\) [mice.impute.norm.nob]
    • Bayesian linear regression imputation with \(m=1\) [mice.impute.norm]
    • Bayesian linear regression imputation with \(m=5\) [mice.impute.norm]
    • Predictive mean matching imputation with \(m=1\) [mice.impute.pmm]
    • Predictive mean matching imputation with \(m=5\) [mice.impute.pmm]
    1. calculate the same statistical properties as under (3) on each of the \(m\) imputed sets
    1. Run the analysis model on each of the \(m\) imputed sets
    1. Combine the \(m\) statistics and parameters from (5b) and (5c) into single inferences`
  1. Analyze the simulation results by
    1. Calculating the average parameters and statistics over the nsim = 1000 simulations
    1. Plotting the distributions of the statistics and parameters with e.g. boxplots
    1. Calculating for all statistics and parameters the bootstrap CI.
    1. Calculating for all parameters the parametric CI cf. Rubin’s rules.
    1. Calculating the 95% coverage rates of the parameters and statistics (bootstrap CI and parametric CI)
  1. Evaluate the results and determine if and when mice would yield valid imputed sets.
